our aim is to build a housing price prediction model . As a person who is looking for a home and needs to know in a certain area how much a house cost, will be considering essential things which meets all basic requirements . #roads #basic utilities #nearest to town or not(to ensure proper hospitality , education etc) #vehicle space #family size which includes rooms for each member #furnished or not # bathrooms # a good kitchen

Checking if we can extract these much details from the given data

LotShape , LandSlope ,LandContour are the properites related with shape of the area . I would not wish to consider these factors in our model .

Assuming in general: Lot shape , inlination all are not factors which users prefer while checking the prices

Lot configuration - That depends on vegetation, maintenance and need for space. The location and neighborhood matter and then there are taxes, upkeep. Some people don’t want to do a lot of maintenance. There are 2 sides to most things. So as a seller it matters !! So adding up lot configuration into our aim

In real estate, above grade means the portion of a home that is above the ground. The term is usually used to describe a room or square footage. For example, 3 bedrooms above grade means 3 bedrooms that are not in a basement. The term above grade is used to give more information about where things are located in a home. Many homes in Edmonton have basements, and many of those basements are very usable, desirable areas, but the fact of the matter is they are still basements, and basement areas are not as desirable as above ground areas.

In [191]:
#iqr method
num=final_data[['LotArea','SalePrice']]
for i in num:
    q1=np.percentile(num,25,interpolation='midpoint')
    q2=np.percentile(num,50,interpolation='midpoint')
    q3=np.percentile(num,75,interpolation='midpoint')
    iqr=q3-q1
    up_lim=q3+1.5*iqr
    low_lim=q1-1.*iqr
    ind1=data.select_dtypes(include=['float','integer'])[i]>up_lim
    ind2=data.select_dtypes(include=['float','integer'])[i]<low_lim
    #data.drop(data.loc[ind1].index,inplace=True)
    # data.drop(data.loc[ind2].index,inplace=True

In [197]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score,mean_squared_error
lr=LinearRegression()
lr.fit(x_train,y_train)
y_pred=lr.predict(x_test)
print('R2_score of the model {} ----  mean_squared_error {}'.format(r2_score(y_pred,y_test),mean_squared_error(y_pred,y_test)))
